Describe shows us various statistics for columns that have numbers as their data. Count tells us how many non-empty rows we have. All columns have all of their data, except for age which lacks some data. Mean shows us the average. Std shows us the devation. Min shows us the smallest number and max the largest. The 25% row shows us the 25% percentile, meaning 25% of our data is more than the number in the column. The same is true for the 50% and 75% rows.

We replaced NaN ages with the mean of all ages, and we removed the cabin column as most of it were NaN and thus were useless. The advantages of replacing null numbers with the mean are that if the data is small, our accuracy won't decrease by a lot and fixes our data loss. The disatvantages are that if the mean is too far from what the NaN numbers were, then our new numbers will be very off from reality.

In [565]:
starting_time1 = t.time()
queenstown1 =  titanic.loc[titanic["Embarked"] == 1]
num_of_queenstown = queenstown1.count()[0]
sum_fare = 0
for i in (queenstown1['Fare']):
    sum_fare += i
mean_fare = sum_fare / num_of_queenstown
ending_time1 = t.time()
execution_time1 = (ending_time1 - starting_time1) * 1000
print("Average fare of passengers embarked from Queenstown:",mean_fare,"\nExecution time:", execution_time1, "milliseconds")

Average fare of passengers embarked from Queenstown: 13.276029870129872 
Execution time: 4.00233268737793 milliseconds

As the execution time of vectorization is nearly third of a for loop (1ms for the former and 3ms for the latter), this proves that the pandas library and vectorization are much more time efficient than python's for loop.

In [568]:
def comparisonPdf(survivor_mean, survivor_std, dead_mean, dead_std, column_name):
    x = np.linspace(survivor_mean - (3 * survivor_std), survivor_mean + (3 * survivor_std), 100)
    plt.plot(x, stats.norm.pdf(x,survivor_mean, survivor_std))
    y = np.linspace(dead_mean - (3 * dead_std), dead_mean + (3 * dead_std), 100)
    plt.plot(y, stats.norm.pdf(y,dead_mean, dead_std))
    plt.legend(["Survived", "Died"], loc = 'upper left')
    plt.title(f'Survivor vs Dead {column_name} Comparison')
    plt.show()

survivor = normalized_titanic.loc[titanic["Survived"] == 1]
survivor_mean = survivor.mean()
survivor_std = survivor.std()
dead = normalized_titanic.loc[titanic["Survived"] == 0]
dead_mean = dead.mean()
dead_std = dead.std()

comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Pclass"], survivor_std["Pclass"], dead_mean["Pclass"], dead_std["Pclass"], "Pclass")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Sex"], survivor_std["Sex"], dead_mean["Sex"], dead_std["Sex"], "Sex")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Age"], survivor_std["Age"], dead_mean["Age"], dead_std["Age"], "Age")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["SibSp"], survivor_std["SibSp"], dead_mean["SibSp"], dead_std["SibSp"], "SibSp")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Parch"], survivor_std["Parch"], dead_mean["Parch"], dead_std["Parch"], "Parch")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Fare"], survivor_std["Fare"], dead_mean["Fare"], dead_std["Fare"], "Fare")
comparisonPdf(survivor_mean["Embarked"], survivor_std["Embarked"], dead_mean["Embarked"], dead_std["Embarked"], "Embarked")

The best predictor has the biggest difference between the two curve's means, lowest variance, and the least amount of area covered between the two curves.

Therefore sex is the best predictor based on these three characteristics.

In [584]:
def predictor(sex):
    survived = stats.norm.pdf(sex,survivor_mean["Sex"], survivor_std["Sex"])
    dead = stats.norm.pdf(sex,dead_mean["Sex"], dead_std["Sex"])
    if survived > dead:
        return 'yes'
    else:
        return 'no'
